==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Study
<hw>Stud"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Studies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>studie</ets>, L.
<ets>studium</ets>, akin to <ets>studere</ets> to study; possibly akin
to Gr. <?/ haste, zeal, <?/ to hasten; cf. OF. <ets>estudie</ets>,
<ets>estude</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tude</ets>. Cf. <er>Etude</er>,
<er>Student</er>, <er>Studio</er>, <er>Study</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A setting of the mind or thoughts upon
a subject; hence, application of mind to books, arts, or science, or to
any subject, for the purpose of acquiring knowledge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hammond . . . spent thirteen hours of the day in
<qex>study</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Fell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Study</qex> gives strength to the mind; conversation,
grace.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mental occupation; absorbed or thoughtful attention;
meditation; contemplation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Just men they seemed, and all their <qex>study</qex> bent⟦br⟧
To worship God aright, and know his works.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any particular branch of learning that is studied;
any object of attentive consideration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Holy Scriptures, especially the New Testament, are her daily
<qex>study</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The proper <qex>study</qex> of mankind is man.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A building or apartment devoted to study or to
literary work.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His cheery little <xex>study</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Hawthorne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>A representation or rendering
of any object or scene intended, not for exhibition as an original work
of art, but for the information, instruction, or assistance of the
maker; <as>as, a <ex>study</ex> of heads or of hands for a figure
picture</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A piece for special practice. See
<er>Etude</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Study</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Study
<hw>Stud"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Studied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Studying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>studien</ets>, OF. <ets>estudier</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tudier</ets>. See <er>Study</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To fix the mind closely upon a subject; to dwell upon
anything in thought; to muse; to ponder.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I found a moral first, and then <qex>studied</qex> for a
fable.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To apply the mind to books or learning.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To endeavor diligently; to be zealous.</def>
<rj><au>1 Thes. iv. 11.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Study</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Study
<hw>Stud"y</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To apply the mind to;
to read and examine for the purpose of learning and understanding;
<as>as, to <ex>study</ex> law or theology; to <ex>study</ex>
languages</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To consider attentively; to examine closely; <as>as,
to <ex>study</ex> the work of nature</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Study</qex> thyself; what rank or what degree⟦br⟧
The wise Creator has ordained for thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To form or arrange by previous thought; to con over,
as in committing to memory; <as>as, to <ex>study</ex> a
speech</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make an object of study; to aim at sedulously; to
devote one's thoughts to; <as>as, to <ex>study</ex> the welfare of
others; to <ex>study</ex> variety in composition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For their heart <qex>studieth</qex> destruction.</q>
<rj><qau>Prov. xxiv. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stufa</ent>⟦br⟧
